com.bigdata.bop.joinGraph.fast

Class DefaultEvaluationPlan2

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.bigdata.bop.joinGraph.fast.DefaultEvaluationPlan2
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    IEvaluationPlan

    public class DefaultEvaluationPlan2
extends Object
implements IEvaluationPlan
    The evaluation order is determined by analysis of the propagation of bindings. The most selective predicate is chosen first (having the fewest unbound variables with ties broken by a range count on the data) and "fake" bindings are propagated to the other predicates in the tail. This process is repeated until all variables are bound and an evaluation order has been determined.

      • getOrder

        public int[] getOrder()
        Description copied from interface: IEvaluationPlan
        Return the evaluation order.
        Specified by:
        getOrder in interface IEvaluationPlan
        Returns:
        The evaluation order. This is an array of indices into the predicates in the tail of the rule. Each tail predicate must be used exactly once. The elements in this array are the order in which each tail predicate will be evaluated. The index into the array is the index of the tail predicate whose evaluation order you want. So [2,0,1] says that the predicates will be evaluated in the order tail[2], then tail[0], then tail[1].

      • rangeCount

        public long rangeCount(int tailIndex)
        Return the range count for the predicate, ignoring any bindings. The range count for the tail predicate is cached the first time it is requested and returned from the cache thereafter. The range counts are requested using the "non-exact" range count query, so the range counts are actually the upper bound. However, if the upper bound is ZERO (0) then the range count really is ZERO (0).
        Specified by:
        rangeCount in interface IEvaluationPlan
        Parameters:
        tailIndex - The index of the predicate in the tail of the rule.
        Returns:
        The range count for that tail predicate.

      • computeJoinCardinality

        protected long computeJoinCardinality(com.bigdata.bop.joinGraph.fast.DefaultEvaluationPlan2.IJoinDimension d1,
                          com.bigdata.bop.joinGraph.fast.DefaultEvaluationPlan2.IJoinDimension d2)
        This is the secret sauce. There are three possibilities for computing the join cardinality, which we are defining as the upper-bound for solutions for a particular join. First, if there are no shared variables then the cardinality will just be the simple sum of the cardinality of each join dimension. If there are shared variables but no unshared variables, then the cardinality will be the minimum cardinality from the join dimensions. If there are shared variables but also some unshared variables, then the join cardinality will be the maximum cardinality from each join dimension.

        Any join involving an optional will have infinite cardinality, so that optionals get placed at the end.

        Parameters:
        d1 - the first join dimension
        d2 - the second join dimension
        Returns:
        the join cardinality
